<Layout title="Ch 8: Evidence Has a Trajectory — Methodeutics" favicon="🔭">
  <main>
    <a href="/reading/methodeutics/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to methodeutics</a>

    <h1>Evidence Has a Trajectory</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Chapter 8 &middot; de Finetti 1937, Ville 1939, Wald 1947, Robbins 1967, Shafer 2021, Ramdas 2023</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">You run an A/B test on two code variants. B converts 12% better than A, p &lt; .01, sample size 50,000. You ship B. Six months later, B is worse than A ever was. The snapshot lied. This chapter introduces a measure of evidence &mdash; the e-value &mdash; that preserves the temporal structure the p-value threw away.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Chapters 4&ndash;7 built the abductive primitive. You can generate hypotheses from a surprising observation. You can select which experiment to run next. But after the experiment runs and data arrives, how do you know the hypothesis is right?</p>

    <p>The standard answer is the p-value: collect a fixed sample, compute a test statistic, compare to a threshold. If p &lt; 0.05, declare significance. The p-value is a scalar computed at a single moment from a fixed sample. It compresses the entire temporal structure of the evidence into one number. That compression is not a convenience. It is a requirement. Peek at the data mid-experiment and the false positive guarantee breaks. The math demands you look once.</p>

    <p>This chapter traces a 90-year lineage of work that removes that demand. The result is a measure of evidence that you can compute at every observation, that you can stop collecting whenever you want, and whose error guarantee holds at every moment. The evidence is no longer a scalar. It is a trajectory. And preserving that trajectory makes temporal patterns — including patterns that may reveal system dynamics — available for analysis.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Three snapshots that lied</h2>

    <p>Before the theory: three cases where compressing evidence to a snapshot produced catastrophic decisions.</p>

    <h3>Google: the feedback loop</h3>

    <p>Google <a href="https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/2783258.2788583">A/B-tested ad load</a>: more ads per page, more revenue per session, ship it. The test assumed stationarity &mdash; that the treatment effect would not change over the measurement window. It also assumed no interference &mdash; that each user's behavior was independent of every other user's. Both assumptions reduce to one: no feedback. The treatment enters, the outcome exits, nothing loops back.</p>

    <p>Long-term measurement revealed the loop. Users learned to ignore ads. Click-through rates degraded over months. Ad blindness spread through the user base as a learned behavior. Google cut mobile ad load by 50%. The snapshot said "more ads = more revenue." The trajectory said "more ads = more revenue now, less revenue later, and the crossover happens outside your test window."</p>

    <h3>Boeing: oscillation killed 346 people</h3>

    <p>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maneuvering_Characteristics_Augmentation_System">Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System (MCAS)</a> read a single sensor snapshot: nose too high. Correct response: push it down. Correct logic, wrong sensor. The angle-of-attack sensor was faulty. MCAS pushed the nose down. Pilots trimmed up. MCAS pushed again. Two subsystems fighting. The oscillation diverged. Lion Air Flight 610. Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302. 346 dead.</p>

    <p>Nobody was watching the trajectory. Each individual MCAS activation was locally correct &mdash; the snapshot said "nose too high, push down." The oscillation between MCAS and pilot inputs was the signal. A system that tracked the temporal pattern of its own corrections would have seen the fight. The snapshot saw only the current angle.</p>

    <h3>Vioxx: delayed cardiovascular risk</h3>

    <p>Rofecoxib (Vioxx) <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rofecoxib">passed its 9-month trial</a>: fewer gastrointestinal bleeds than naproxen, ship it. The cardiovascular risk emerged at 18 months, past the trial window. Cumulative thrombotic damage, invisible in the snapshot. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(05)17864-5">88,000&ndash;140,000 excess coronary events</a> before the drug was pulled.</p>

    <p>The trial tested for GI bleeds over 9 months. It found what it tested for. The cardiovascular trajectory was in the data &mdash; thrombotic risk accumulated monotonically &mdash; but the fixed-sample test could not see it because the test window ended before the risk crossed the detection threshold.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>What all three share</h2>

    <p>Each failure has the same structure:</p>

    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 mb-4">
      <li class="mb-1">A system with feedback (users adapt, pilots fight the computer, cumulative organ damage).</li>
      <li class="mb-1">A test that assumes no feedback (stationarity, independence, fixed time window).</li>
      <li class="mb-1">A scalar summary (p-value, revenue delta, hazard ratio) computed at a single moment.</li>
      <li class="mb-1">A decision shipped on the scalar.</li>
      <li class="mb-1">A trajectory that would have revealed the danger, had anyone preserved it.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>This is <a href="/reading/scientific-method/meehl-1967/">Meehl's structural flaw</a> at industrial scale. In 1967 Meehl showed that directional predictions in soft psychology corroborate nothing because the crud factor guarantees significance. The same structure &mdash; directional prediction, snapshot window, no trajectory &mdash; now ships products and drugs. Soft psychology published non-replicable findings. A/B testing culture adopted the same structure — directional predictions, fixed sample sizes, ship on significance.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The betting line</h2>

    <p>The alternative to snapshot testing has a 90-year lineage. Six contributions, each building on the last. The thread is thin &mdash; the key ideas ran parallel to Fisher's fixed-horizon view for decades before converging.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Year</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Who</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">Contribution</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">1937</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruno_de_Finetti">de Finetti</a></td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Probability as coherent betting. If your beliefs can be Dutch-booked, they aren't probabilities. Established that evidence is a bet, not a frequency.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">1939</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Ville">Ville</a></td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Proved that von Mises' definition of randomness fails. Introduced <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martingale_(probability_theory)">martingales</a> as a test of randomness: if you can make money betting against a sequence, it isn't random.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">1947</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_Wald">Wald</a></td>
            <td class="text-gray-400"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequential_analysis">Sequential analysis</a>. You don't need a fixed sample size. Collect data one observation at a time, decide to stop or continue after each one. The first formal framework for optional stopping.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">1953</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_L._Doob">Doob</a></td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optional_stopping_theorem">optional stopping theorem</a>. A supermartingale cannot grow in expectation, even if you choose when to stop. This is the mathematical backbone: honest betting under the null can't make you rich on average, regardless of your stopping rule.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">1967</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbert_Robbins">Robbins</a> &amp; Darling</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Proved that confidence sequences &mdash; confidence intervals valid at every sample size &mdash; are achievable. You can peek at every observation and the coverage guarantee holds.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">2019&ndash;2023</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300"><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.07801">Ramdas</a>, <a href="/reading/scientific-method/shafer-2021/">Shafer</a>, <a href="https://academic.oup.com/jrsssb/article/86/5/1091/7623686">Gr&uuml;nwald</a></td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Unified the lineage under the name <strong>e-values</strong>. Proved composability, anytime validity, and connections to game-theoretic probability. Made it usable.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>De Finetti said evidence is a bet. Ville said you can test a hypothesis by trying to make money against it. Wald said you don't need to fix your sample size. Doob proved the guarantee holds no matter when you stop. Robbins showed confidence intervals can hold at every peek. Ramdas, Shafer, and Gr&uuml;nwald unified it into a framework and named the central object.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>E-values: definition from scratch</h2>

    <p>A <strong>p-value</strong> is the probability of seeing data at least as extreme as what you observed, assuming the null hypothesis is true. If p is small, the data is surprising under the null. Smaller p = more evidence against the null.</p>

    <p>An <strong>e-value</strong> is the payoff of a bet against the null hypothesis. If the null is true, the expected payoff is at most 1:</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>E[e] &le; 1 &nbsp;&nbsp; under the null</code></pre>

    <p>That's the entire definition. An e-value is a non-negative random variable whose expectation under the null is at most 1. Large values (e &gt;&gt; 1) mean the null is losing the bet badly. In the likelihood-ratio case, an e-value of 20 can be interpreted as the data being 20 times more consistent with the alternative than the null.</p>

    <p>The constraint E[e] &le; 1 is the <strong>supermartingale property</strong>. A supermartingale is a stochastic process whose expected future value is at most its current value. If you are betting against the null and the null is true, your wealth cannot grow on average. If your wealth grows anyway, the null is losing.</p>

    <h3>Why "at most 1" and not "equals 1"</h3>

    <p>A martingale has E[e] = 1 exactly. A supermartingale relaxes this to E[e] &le; 1. The relaxation matters because it makes e-values composable. If you run two sequential experiments producing e-values e<sub>1</sub> and e<sub>2</sub>, their product e<sub>1</sub> &times; e<sub>2</sub> is also an e-value. The supermartingale property guarantees it: two honest bets composed are still an honest bet. This composition does not require any correction for multiple testing. It is exact.</p>

    <p>P-values do not compose this way. If you run two tests and multiply their p-values, the result is not a valid p-value. You need corrections (Bonferroni, Holm, BH) and those corrections are conservative &mdash; they throw away statistical power to maintain the guarantee. E-values compose for free.</p>

    <h3>Anytime validity</h3>

    <p>The deepest property: you can compute an e-value at every observation and the guarantee holds at each one. There is no peeking penalty. There is no alpha spending. You look whenever you want, stop whenever you want, and the false positive rate is controlled at every moment.</p>

    <p>This is Doob's optional stopping theorem in action. A supermartingale evaluated at any stopping time is still a supermartingale. The math does not care when you look or why you stopped. It holds unconditionally.</p>

    <p>Contrast with a p-value. If you compute a p-value at n=100 and it's 0.06 (not significant), then peek again at n=200 and it's 0.04 (significant), your false positive rate is no longer 5%. By peeking twice, you inflated it. The p-value guarantee requires exactly one look. One. The e-value guarantee holds at every look.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The key insight: trajectory preserves temporal structure</h2>

    <p>A p-value compresses evidence over time into a scalar. An e-value stream preserves evidence over time. The system's dynamics are in the temporal structure. Compress to a scalar and they're gone. Keep the stream and they're there.</p>

    <p>This is a mathematical property of the two frameworks, not an empirical finding. No experiment is needed to see why.</p>

    <p>Point an e-value stream at a system with feedback. The evidence trajectory preserves temporal patterns that a terminal scalar discards — patterns that may reveal the system's dynamics.</p>

    <p><strong>Smoking and stress.</strong> Test whether smoking reduces stress. The e-value climbs after each cigarette (relief), falls during withdrawal (stress spikes), climbs on relapse. The oscillation in your evidence <em>is</em> the addiction cycle. A two-week snapshot would say "smoking reduces stress, p &lt; .05." The e-value trajectory shows the loop.</p>

    <p><strong>Ad load.</strong> An e-value stream tracking revenue per session would climb for the first weeks (more ads = more revenue), then flatten (ad blindness developing), then decline (revenue loss from degraded engagement). The inflection point in the evidence trajectory is the moment the feedback loop activates. A fixed-sample test that ends before the inflection sees only the climb.</p>

    <p><strong>MCAS.</strong> An e-value tracking "does the flight control correction succeed?" would oscillate. Each correction pushes the nose down (evidence for success), the pilot trims up (evidence resets), MCAS fires again (evidence for success again). The oscillation in the evidence is two subsystems fighting. A snapshot at any single activation says "correction successful."</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Composition: evidence in installments</h2>

    <p>E-values compose multiplicatively across sequential experiments. This is the structural advantage.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Framework</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Method</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Sample size</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">Composition</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Frequentist</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Fixed</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Fixed</td><td class="text-gray-400">Requires correction (Bonferroni, etc.)</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Bayesian</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Fixed</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Variable</td><td class="text-gray-400">Requires shared prior</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">E-value</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Variable</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Variable</td><td class="text-gray-400">Multiply. No correction needed.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Run ten small experiments, each isolating one variable, tracked over time. The evidence composes multiplicatively. Experiment A gives e<sub>1</sub> = 3 (suggestive). Experiment B gives e<sub>2</sub> = 4 (suggestive). Neither is strong alone. But e<sub>1</sub> &times; e<sub>2</sub> = 12 &mdash; strong combined evidence. The product is a valid e-value with no correction.</p>

    <p>You can change your test, your sampling strategy, your hypothesis mid-stream, and the evidence still composes. The supermartingale guarantee holds regardless. You cannot do "try things and accumulate evidence" with a fixed method. You need the freedom to change what you're doing based on what you're learning. E-values grant that freedom.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Code: e-value trajectory for a sequential test</h2>

    <p>A simple sequential test. Observations arrive one at a time. Under the null, they are drawn from N(0, 1). Under the alternative, N(&mu;, 1) for some &mu; &gt; 0. At each step, compute the likelihood ratio &mdash; the simplest e-value &mdash; and track the trajectory.</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code><span class="hl-keyword">import</span> math
<span class="hl-keyword">import</span> random

<span class="hl-keyword">def</span> <span class="hl-builtin">e_value_trajectory</span>(observations, mu_alt=<span class="hl-number">0.5</span>):
    <span class="hl-string">"""Compute cumulative e-value trajectory via likelihood ratio.

    E-value at step t = product of likelihood ratios up to t.
    Under H0: X_i ~ N(0,1). Under H1: X_i ~ N(mu_alt, 1).
    Likelihood ratio for one observation:
        L(x) = exp(mu_alt * x - mu_alt^2 / 2)
    Cumulative e-value: product of L(x_i) for i = 1..t.
    """</span>
    trajectory = []
    log_e = <span class="hl-number">0.0</span>

    <span class="hl-keyword">for</span> x <span class="hl-keyword">in</span> observations:
        <span class="hl-comment"># Log-likelihood ratio for one observation</span>
        log_lr = mu_alt * x - (mu_alt ** <span class="hl-number">2</span>) / <span class="hl-number">2</span>
        log_e += log_lr
        trajectory.append(math.exp(log_e))

    <span class="hl-keyword">return</span> trajectory

<span class="hl-keyword">def</span> <span class="hl-builtin">p_value_at_t</span>(observations):
    <span class="hl-string">"""Two-sided z-test p-value computed at the end of the sample."""</span>
    n = <span class="hl-builtin">len</span>(observations)
    <span class="hl-keyword">if</span> n == <span class="hl-number">0</span>:
        <span class="hl-keyword">return</span> <span class="hl-number">1.0</span>
    mean = <span class="hl-builtin">sum</span>(observations) / n
    z = mean * math.sqrt(n)
    <span class="hl-comment"># One-sided p-value via normal CDF approximation</span>
    p = <span class="hl-number">0.5</span> * math.erfc(z / math.sqrt(<span class="hl-number">2</span>))
    <span class="hl-keyword">return</span> p


<span class="hl-comment"># --- Scenario 1: Null is true (no effect) ---</span>
random.seed(<span class="hl-number">42</span>)
null_obs = [random.gauss(<span class="hl-number">0</span>, <span class="hl-number">1</span>) <span class="hl-keyword">for</span> _ <span class="hl-keyword">in</span> <span class="hl-builtin">range</span>(<span class="hl-number">100</span>)]
null_traj = e_value_trajectory(null_obs)

<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">"=== Null is true (no real effect) ==="</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=10:  &#123;null_traj[9]:.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=50:  &#123;null_traj[49]:.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=100: &#123;null_traj[99]:.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"P-value at t=100: &#123;p_value_at_t(null_obs):.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>()

<span class="hl-comment"># --- Scenario 2: Alternative is true (real effect, mu=0.3) ---</span>
alt_obs = [random.gauss(<span class="hl-number">0.3</span>, <span class="hl-number">1</span>) <span class="hl-keyword">for</span> _ <span class="hl-keyword">in</span> <span class="hl-builtin">range</span>(<span class="hl-number">100</span>)]
alt_traj = e_value_trajectory(alt_obs, mu_alt=<span class="hl-number">0.5</span>)

<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">"=== Alternative is true (mu=0.3) ==="</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=10:  &#123;alt_traj[9]:.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=50:  &#123;alt_traj[49]:.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=100: &#123;alt_traj[99]:.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"P-value at t=100: &#123;p_value_at_t(alt_obs):.4f&#125;"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>()

<span class="hl-comment"># --- Scenario 3: System with feedback (effect reverses at t=50) ---</span>
feedback_obs = (
    [random.gauss(<span class="hl-number">0.5</span>, <span class="hl-number">1</span>) <span class="hl-keyword">for</span> _ <span class="hl-keyword">in</span> <span class="hl-builtin">range</span>(<span class="hl-number">50</span>)] +  <span class="hl-comment"># positive effect</span>
    [random.gauss(-<span class="hl-number">0.3</span>, <span class="hl-number">1</span>) <span class="hl-keyword">for</span> _ <span class="hl-keyword">in</span> <span class="hl-builtin">range</span>(<span class="hl-number">50</span>)]   <span class="hl-comment"># effect reverses</span>
)
feedback_traj = e_value_trajectory(feedback_obs, mu_alt=<span class="hl-number">0.5</span>)

<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">"=== Feedback system (effect reverses at t=50) ==="</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=25:  &#123;feedback_traj[24]:.4f&#125;  (rising)"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=50:  &#123;feedback_traj[49]:.4f&#125;  (peak)"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=75:  &#123;feedback_traj[74]:.4f&#125;  (falling)"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"E-value at t=100: &#123;feedback_traj[99]:.4f&#125;  (collapsed)"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"P-value at t=50:  &#123;p_value_at_t(feedback_obs[:50]):.4f&#125;  (snapshot at peak)"</span>)
<span class="hl-builtin">print</span>(<span class="hl-string">f"P-value at t=100: &#123;p_value_at_t(feedback_obs):.4f&#125;  (snapshot at end)"</span>)</code></pre>

    <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-2 mb-6">Output:</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>=== Null is true (no real effect) ===
E-value at t=10:  0.1432
E-value at t=50:  0.0005
E-value at t=100: 0.0001
P-value at t=100: 0.2802

=== Alternative is true (mu=0.3) ===
E-value at t=10:  2.3119
E-value at t=50:  68.6328
E-value at t=100: 73236.5661
P-value at t=100: 0.0000

=== Feedback system (effect reverses at t=50) ===
E-value at t=25:  122.3931  (rising)
E-value at t=50:  1161.3707  (peak)
E-value at t=75:  1.5770  (falling)
E-value at t=100: 0.0027  (collapsed)
P-value at t=50:  0.0001  (snapshot at peak)
P-value at t=100: 0.0942  (snapshot at end)</code></pre>

    <p>Three scenarios. Three stories.</p>

    <p><strong>Null is true:</strong> the e-value drops below 1 immediately and keeps falling. By t=100 it is 0.0001 &mdash; the bet against the null has been thoroughly lost. The supermartingale property in action: under the null, honest betting cannot grow in expectation. Individual paths can fluctuate, but the trend is downward. The p-value at 100 agrees: not significant.</p>

    <p><strong>Alternative is true:</strong> the e-value climbs steadily. By t=100, e = 73,237 &mdash; overwhelming evidence. You could have stopped at t=50 (e &asymp; 69, already strong) or continued. The guarantee held at every peek. The trajectory shows a monotone climb: the evidence is accumulating, not oscillating.</p>

    <p><strong>Feedback system:</strong> this is the Google ad-load scenario. The effect is real for the first 50 observations, then reverses. The e-value climbs to 1,161 at t=50 (strong evidence), then <em>collapses</em> as the reversal erodes the accumulated evidence. By t=100, e = 0.003 &mdash; the bet has been lost. A p-value computed at t=50 says p = 0.0001 &mdash; highly significant. A p-value computed at t=100 says p = 0.09 &mdash; borderline. Two different scalars, two different conclusions, no way to reconcile them within the p-value framework. The e-value trajectory tells the whole story: rise, peak, collapse. The shape of the trajectory is the shape of the system.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Why the p-value compresses</h2>

    <p>The p-value's limitation is not a design flaw. It is a mathematical consequence of how the guarantee works.</p>

    <p>A p-value controls the <strong>type I error rate at a single, predetermined stopping time</strong>. If you fix n in advance and compute once, then P(p &lt; &alpha; | H<sub>0</sub>) = &alpha;. The guarantee is conditional on looking exactly once. Peeking at t=50 and again at t=100 gives you two chances to cross the threshold, inflating the error rate.</p>

    <p>An e-value controls the error rate <strong>uniformly over all stopping times</strong>. By Markov's inequality and the supermartingale property: for any stopping time &tau;,</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>P(e<sub>&tau;</sub> &ge; 1/&alpha;) &le; &alpha; &nbsp;&nbsp; under the null</code></pre>

    <p>This holds for <em>any</em> stopping time &mdash; fixed, random, data-dependent, adversarial. The proof is three lines and uses only Doob's optional stopping theorem. The p-value guarantee requires the stopping time to be independent of the data. The e-value guarantee does not.</p>

    <p>The tradeoff: e-value tests may lose power versus fixed-time tests at any single sample size. If you commit in advance to looking exactly once at exactly n observations, the p-value is more powerful. The e-value pays for its flexibility with a constant-factor loss in efficiency at any single time point. What it buys with that payment is the entire trajectory.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Connection to Part II</h2>

    <p>The economy of research (<a href="/reading/methodeutics/ch07-economy-of-research/">Chapter 7</a>) selects which experiment to run. The e-value tracks what the experiment says over time. The two connect directly:</p>

    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 mb-4">
      <li class="mb-2"><strong>Generate</strong> hypotheses via abduction (Chapters 4&ndash;6).</li>
      <li class="mb-2"><strong>Select</strong> the next experiment via information gain per unit cost (Chapter 7).</li>
      <li class="mb-2"><strong>Run</strong> the experiment and track the e-value trajectory (this chapter).</li>
      <li class="mb-2"><strong>Read</strong> the trajectory's shape to classify the system's dynamics (Chapter 9).</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Step 3 is new. Before e-values, step 2 fed directly into a terminal decision: run, compute p, decide. Now there is a trajectory between the experiment and the decision. That trajectory carries information that the terminal scalar discards.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>What this chapter does not solve</h2>

    <p>You have the trajectory. It oscillates. Is the system fighting itself (two subsystems in a feedback loop, like MCAS vs. pilots), or is your measurement noisy (the underlying effect is constant but your observations are high-variance)?</p>

    <p>Oscillation in the e-value trajectory has at least two interpretations. One is structural: the system has cyclic dynamics and the evidence reflects them. The other is statistical: the effect is real but weak, and finite-sample noise creates apparent oscillation. The trajectory alone cannot distinguish the two.</p>

    <p>To read the trajectory's shape &mdash; to classify whether the evidence is converging, diverging, oscillating, or chaotic &mdash; you need a classification scheme. That scheme exists. The math for classifying iterative sequences (convergence rate, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyapunov_exponent">Lyapunov exponents</a>, stability analysis) has been developed for decades in dynamical systems theory. The question is whether it applies to evidence trajectories.</p>

    <p>That is the subject of <a href="/reading/methodeutics/ch09-four-bins/">Chapter 9</a>.</p>

